#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Studio Method"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Weld on undyed warp: a process sequence"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Warp planning & sett"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Weld is a transparent dye — its value shifts dramatically with the ground it lands on. Begin with the warp colour decision: undyed linen gives a warm, greenish-yellow; bleached cotton moves the result toward a cleaner chrome. Thread count (sett) determines how much ground shows through the weave structure, which in turn sets the saturation ceiling."
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Mordanting"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Alum (potassium aluminium sulphate) at 15–20% WOF. Dissolve in hot water, add fibre at 60°C, raise slowly to 80°C over 45 minutes, hold one hour. Exhaust the bath — discarding mordant solution is waste; the fibres take only what they need. Cool slowly in the bath before rinsing."
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Weld bath"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Fresh or dried Reseda luteola, 200% WOF for a full extraction. Simmer the plant material separately, strain, add fibres to the cooled liquor. Heat slowly to 80°C over 30 minutes, hold 45 minutes. The colour develops during the hold — do not rush the exhaust. Rinse in water of gradually decreasing temperature."
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Finishing & lightfastness"
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "Weld on alum-mordanted linen rates 5–6 on the Blue Wool scale — good lightfastness, not archival. Store away from direct light. A second mordant bath with iron (ferrous sulphate, 2% WOF) after dyeing will deepen the yellow toward olive and improve fastness by a half-grade."
msgstr ""

#: patterns/process-notation.php
msgid "WOF = Weight of Fibre. All percentages by weight. Results vary with water chemistry and plant source."
msgstr ""

